tweets.text:
@kazoku886 CAPTURE folder plus Obsidian plus Claude is the exact right minimal version.

You do not need more than three components to start.

The system that runs when you do nothing is the only system that actually runs.

@nagarjuncreates The mental load reduction is the part that compounds most noticeably.

You stop carrying the cognitive weight of remembering to file things.

The system holds it. You just show up and work.

@capitanb_sails The graveyard of untagged files is exactly what the cron job fixes.

You do not have to go back and tag everything manually. 

You let Claude process new captures correctly going forward and the vault gets progressively more organized every day without a cleanup project.

@britanianec Boris identifying the 14% context loss before a single word is typed is the insight that changes how you think about everything in the setup layer.

The session starts losing before you type anything.

CLAUDE.md is the fix that reclaims that loss and turns it into leverage instead.

@JoeJoe8562 One layer deeper is where all the leverage lives.

Surface users get surface results. 

The people who understand what is actually happening underneath the interface get compounding results.

@YotamBlu Copy-pasting prompts is using the interface.

Configuring the system is using the tool.

Most people never cross that line because nobody tells them the line exists.

@dzikyDonnyMaps This is the most useful comment in the thread.

Saving this for everyone who asked about setup complexity. The install is exactly this simple. One docker run command and you are live at localhost:3000.

The Ollama step is optional. If you want to start without local models you can point it at any cloud LLM with an API key and skip the local setup entirely.

@LeaT_Design The Docker Compose takes about 10 minutes on a Friday night.

The $20 a month Perplexity subscription takes 12 months a year.
The ROI math works out pretty quickly.

@EternalEila Perplexica is the original repo name. Vane is what it is being called now.

Same codebase, same architecture. 

The rebrand happened as the project grew beyond its origins as a direct Perplexity clone.

@tawer1O SearxNG handles the search layer out of the box with zero extra configuration.

It connects to Google, Bing, DuckDuckGo, Brave, and 70+ other sources automatically when you spin up the container.

No API keys required for the search layer. You only need API keys if you want to use a cloud LLM instead of running Ollama locally.

@seylorra Maintainer burnout is the silent killer of every great open source project.

The distributed architecture helps here. Anyone can fork and maintain a mirror. The data lives on IPFS and torrents not in one repo controlled by one person.

The real sustainability question is whether the community builds around it fast enough to distribute the maintenance load before Anna burns out alone.
